# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mixed-effects-models
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] In statistics, a **fixed effects model** is a statistical model in which the model parameters are fixed or non-random quantities.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] This is in contrast to random effects models and mixed models in which all or some of the model parameters are random variables.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] In many applications including econometrics and biostatistics a fixed effects model refers to a regression model in which the group means are fixed (non-random) as opposed to a random effects model in which the group means are a random sample from a population.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Generally, data can be grouped according to several observed factors.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] The group means could be modeled as fixed or random effects for each grouping.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] In a fixed effects model each group mean is a group-specific fixed quantity.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] In panel data where longitudinal observations exist for the same subject, fixed effects represent the subject-specific means.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] In panel data analysis the term **fixed effects estimator** (also known as the **within estimator**) is used to refer to an estimator for the coefficients in the regression model including those fixed effects (one time-invariant intercept for each subject).
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Such models assist in controlling for omitted variable bias due to unobserved heterogeneity when this heterogeneity is constant over time.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] This heterogeneity can be removed from the data through differencing, for example by subtracting the group-level average over time, or by taking a first difference which will remove any time invariant components of the model.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] There are two common assumptions made about the individual specific effect: the random effects assumption and the fixed effects assumption.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] The random effects assumption is that the individual-specific effects are uncorrelated with the independent variables.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] The fixed effect assumption is that the individual-specific effects are correlated with the independent variables.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] If the random effects assumption holds, the random effects estimator is more efficient than the fixed effects estimator.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] However, if this assumption does not hold, the random effects estimator is not consistent.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] The Durbin–Wu–Hausman test is often used to discriminate between the fixed and the random effects models.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Unlike $X_{it}$ , $\alpha _{i}$ cannot be directly observed.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Unlike the random effects model where the unobserved $\alpha _{i}$ is independent of $X_{it}$ for all $t=1,...,T$ , the fixed effects (FE) model allows $\alpha _{i}$ to be correlated with the regressor matrix $X_{it}$ .
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Strict exogeneity with respect to the idiosyncratic error term $u_{it}$ is still required.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Since $\alpha _{i}$ is not observable, it cannot be directly controlled for.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Since $\alpha _{i}$ is constant, ${\overline {\alpha _{i}}}=\alpha _{i}$ and hence the effect is eliminated.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] The FE estimator ${\hat {\beta }}_{FE}$ is then obtained by an OLS regression of ${\ddot {y}}$ on ${\ddot {X}}$ .
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Finally, each of the above alternatives can be improved if the series-specific estimation is linear (within a nonlinear model), in which case the direct linear solution for individual series can be programmed in as part of the nonlinear model definition.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] An alternative to the within transformation is the *first difference* transformation, which produces a different estimator.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] The FD estimator ${\hat {\beta }}_{FD}$ is then obtained by an OLS regression of $\Delta y_{it}$ on $\Delta X_{it}$ .
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] When $T=2$ , the first difference and fixed effects estimators are numerically equivalent.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] If the error terms $u_{it}$ are homoskedastic with no serial correlation, the fixed effects estimator is more efficient than the first difference estimator.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] If $u_{it}$ follows a random walk, however, the first difference estimator is more efficient.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] For the special two period case ( $T=2$ ), the fixed effects (FE) estimator and the first difference (FD) estimator are numerically equivalent.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] This is because the FE estimator effectively "doubles the data set" used in the FD estimator.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Gary Chamberlain's method, a generalization of the within estimator, replaces $\alpha _{i}$ with its linear projection onto the explanatory variables.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] which can be estimated by minimum distance estimation.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Need to have more than one time-variant regressor ( X ) and time-invariant regressor ( Z ) and at least one X and one Z that are uncorrelated with $\alpha _{i}$ .
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Estimating $\gamma$ via OLS on ${\widehat {di}}=Z_{i}\gamma +\varphi _{it}$ using $X_{1}$ and $Z_{1}$ as instruments yields a consistent estimate.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] When there is input uncertainty for the y data, $\delta y$ , then the $\chi ^{2}$ value, rather than the sum of squared residuals, should be minimized.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] then the values and standard deviations for $\mathbf {\beta }$ and $\alpha _{i}$ can be determined via classical ordinary least squares analysis and variance-covariance matrix.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Random effects estimators may be inconsistent sometimes in the long time series limit, if the random effects are misspecified (i.e. the model chosen for the random effects is incorrect).
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] However, the fixed effects model may still be consistent in some situations.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] For example, if the time series being modeled is not stationary, random effects models assuming stationarity may not be consistent in the long-series limit.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] One example of this is if the time series has an upward trend.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] Then, as the series becomes longer, the model revises estimates for the mean of earlier periods upwards, giving increasingly biased predictions of coefficients.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] However, a model with fixed time effects does not pool information across time, and as a result earlier estimates will not be affected.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] In situations like these where the fixed effects model is known to be consistent, the Durbin-Wu-Hausman test can be used to test whether the random effects model chosen is consistent.
[src:mixed-effects-models/fixed-effects-model] If $H_{a}$ is true the consistency of ${\widehat {\beta }}_{RE}$ cannot be guaranteed.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] In statistics, the **intraclass correlation**, or the **intraclass correlation coefficient** (**ICC**), is a descriptive statistic that can be used when quantitative measurements are made on units that are organized into groups.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] It describes how strongly units in the same group resemble each other.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] While it is viewed as a type of correlation, unlike most other correlation measures, it operates on data structured as groups rather than data structured as paired observations.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] The *intraclass correlation* is commonly used to quantify the degree to which individuals with a fixed degree of relatedness (e.g. full siblings) resemble each other in terms of a quantitative trait (see heritability).
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Another prominent application is the assessment of consistency or reproducibility of quantitative measurements made by different observers measuring the same quantity.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] The earliest work on intraclass correlations focused on the case of paired measurements, and the first intraclass correlation (ICC) statistics to be proposed were modifications of the interclass correlation (Pearson correlation).
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Later versions of this statistic used the degrees of freedom 2*N* −1 in the denominator for calculating *s*2 and *N* −1 in the denominator for calculating *r*, so that *s*2 becomes unbiased, and *r* becomes unbiased if *s* is known.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] The key difference between this ICC and the interclass (Pearson) correlation is that the data are pooled to estimate the mean and variance.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] The reason for this is that in the setting where an intraclass correlation is desired, the pairs are considered to be unordered.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] For example, if we are studying the resemblance of twins, there is usually no meaningful way to order the values for the two individuals within a twin pair.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Like the interclass correlation, the intraclass correlation for paired data will be confined to the interval [−1, +1].
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] The intraclass correlation is also defined for data sets with groups having more than 2 values.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] As the number of items per group grows, so does the number of cross-product terms in this expression grows.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] where *K* is the number of data values per group, and ${\bar {x}}_{n}$ is the sample mean of the *n*th group.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] This form is usually attributed to Harris.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] which can be interpreted as the fraction of the total variance that is due to variation between groups.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Ronald Fisher devotes an entire chapter to intraclass correlation in his classic book *Statistical Methods for Research Workers*.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] For data from a population that is completely noise, Fisher's formula produces ICC values that are distributed about 0, i.e. sometimes being negative.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] This is because Fisher designed the formula to be unbiased, and therefore its estimates are sometimes overestimates and sometimes underestimates.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] For small or 0 underlying values in the population, the ICC calculated from a sample may be negative.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Beginning with Ronald Fisher, the intraclass correlation has been regarded within the framework of analysis of variance (ANOVA), and more recently in the framework of random effects models.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] A number of ICC estimators have been proposed.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] where *Y**ij* is the *i*th observation in the *j*th group, *μ* is an unobserved overall mean, *αj* is an unobserved random effect shared by all values in group *j*, and *εij* is an unobserved noise term.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] For the model to be identified, the *αj* and *εij* are assumed to have expected value zero and to be uncorrelated with each other.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Also, the *αj* are assumed to be identically distributed, and the *εij* are assumed to be identically distributed.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] The variance of *αj* is denoted *σ*2 *α* and the variance of *ε**ij* is denoted *σ*2 *ε*.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] With this framework, the ICC is the correlation of two observations from the same group.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] In this, we've used properties of the covariance.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] An advantage of this ANOVA framework is that different groups can have different numbers of data values, which is difficult to handle using the earlier ICC statistics.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] This expression can never be negative (unlike Fisher's original formula) and therefore, in samples from a population which has an ICC of 0, the ICCs in the samples will be higher than the ICC of the population.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] A number of different ICC statistics have been proposed, not all of which estimate the same population parameter.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] There has been considerable debate about which ICC statistics are appropriate for a given use, since they may produce markedly different results for the same data.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] In terms of its algebraic form, Fisher's original ICC is the ICC that most resembles the Pearson correlation coefficient.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] One key difference between the two statistics is that in the ICC, the data are centered and scaled using a pooled mean and standard deviation, whereas in the Pearson correlation, each variable is centered and scaled by its own mean and standard deviation.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] This pooled scaling for the ICC makes sense because all measurements are of the same quantity (albeit on units in different groups).
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] An important property of the Pearson correlation is that it is invariant to application of separate linear transformations to the two variables being compared.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Thus, if we are correlating *X* and *Y*, where, say, *Y* = 2*X* + 1, the Pearson correlation between *X* and *Y* is 1 — a perfect correlation.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] This property does not make sense for the ICC, since there is no basis for deciding which transformation is applied to each value in a group.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] However, if all the data in all groups are subjected to the same linear transformation, the ICC does not change.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] The ICC is used to assess the consistency, or conformity, of measurements made by multiple observers measuring the same quantity.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] For example, if several physicians are asked to score the results of a CT scan for signs of cancer progression, we can ask how consistent the scores are with each other.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] If the truth is known (for example, if the CT scans were on patients who subsequently underwent exploratory surgery), then the focus would generally be on how well the physicians' scores matched the truth.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] If the truth is not known, we can only consider the similarity among the scores.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] An important aspect of this problem is that there is both inter-observer and intra-observer variability.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Inter-observer variability refers to systematic differences among the observers — for example, one physician may consistently score patients at a higher risk level than other physicians.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Intra-observer variability refers to deviations of a particular observer's score on a particular patient that are not part of a systematic difference.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] The ICC is constructed to be applied to exchangeable measurements — that is, grouped data in which there is no meaningful way to order the measurements within a group.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] In assessing conformity among observers, if the same observers rate each element being studied, then systematic differences among observers are likely to exist, which conflicts with the notion of exchangeability.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] If the ICC is used in a situation where systematic differences exist, the result is a composite measure of intra-observer and inter-observer variability.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] One situation where exchangeability might reasonably be presumed to hold would be where a specimen to be scored, say a blood specimen, is divided into multiple aliquots, and the aliquots are measured separately on the same instrument.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] In this case, exchangeability would hold as long as no effect due to the sequence of running the samples was present.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Since the *intraclass correlation coefficient* gives a composite of intra-observer and inter-observer variability, its results are sometimes considered difficult to interpret when the observers are not exchangeable.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Alternative measures such as Cohen's kappa statistic, the Fleiss kappa, and the concordance correlation coefficient have been proposed as more suitable measures of agreement among non-exchangeable observers.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] Notably, the package allows estimation of adjusted ICC (i.e. controlling for other variables) and computes confidence intervals based on parametric bootstrapping and significances based on the permutation of residuals.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] The consistency ICC cannot be estimated in the one-way random effects model, as there is no way to separate the inter-rater and residual variances.
[src:mixed-effects-models/intraclass-correlation] An overview and re-analysis of the three models for the single measures ICC, with an alternative recipe for their use, has also been presented by Liljequist et al.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] A **mixed model**, **mixed-effects model** or **mixed error-component model** is a statistical model containing both fixed effects and random effects.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] These models are useful in a wide variety of disciplines in the physical, biological and social sciences.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] They are particularly useful in settings where repeated measurements are made on the same statistical units (see also longitudinal study), or where measurements are made on clusters of related statistical units.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Mixed models are often preferred over traditional analysis of variance regression models because they don't rely on the independent observations assumption.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Further, they have their flexibility in dealing with missing values and uneven spacing of repeated measurements.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] The Mixed model analysis allows measurements to be explicitly modeled in a wider variety of correlation and variance-covariance avoiding biased estimations structures.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] This page will discuss mainly **linear mixed-effects models** rather than generalized linear mixed models or nonlinear mixed-effects models.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Linear mixed models (LMMs) are statistical models that incorporate fixed and random effects to accurately represent non-independent data structures.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] LMM is an alternative to analysis of variance (ANOVA).
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Often, ANOVA assumes the statistical independence of observations within each group, however, this assumption may not hold in non-independent data, such as multilevel/hierarchical, longitudinal, or correlated datasets.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Non-independent sets are ones in which the variability between outcomes is due to correlations within groups or between groups.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Mixed models properly account for nested structures/hierarchical data structures where observations are influenced by their nested associations.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] For example, when studying education methods involving multiple schools, there are multiple levels of variables to consider.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] The individual level/lower level comprises individual students or teachers within the school.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] The observations obtained from this student/teacher is nested within their school.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] For example, Student A is a unit within the School A.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] At the higher level, the school contains multiple individual students and teachers.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] The school level influences the observations obtained from the students and teachers.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] For Example, School A and School B are the higher levels each with its set of Student A and Student B respectively.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] This represents a hierarchical data scheme.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] A solution to modeling hierarchical data is using linear mixed models.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] LMMs allow us to understand the important effects between and within levels while incorporating the corrections for standard errors for non-independence embedded in the data structure.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] In experimental fields such as social psychology, psycholinguistics, cognitive psychology (and neuroscience), where studies often involve multiple grouping variables, failing to account for random effects can lead to inflated Type I error rates and unreliable conclusions.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] For instance, when analyzing data from experiments that involve both samples of participants and samples of stimuli (e.g., images, scenarios, etc.), ignoring variation in either of these grouping variables (e.g., by averaging over stimuli) can result in misleading conclusions.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] In such cases, researchers can instead treat both participant and stimulus as random effects with LMMs, and in doing so, can correctly account for the variation in their data across multiple grouping variables.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Similarly, when analyzing data from comparative longitudinal surveys, failing to include random effects at all relevant levels—such as country and country-year—can significantly distort the results.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Fixed effects encapsulate the tendencies/trends that are consistent at the levels of primary interest.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] These effects are considered fixed because they are non-random and assumed to be constant for the population being studied.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] For example, when studying education a fixed effect could represent overall school level effects that are consistent across all schools.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] While the hierarchy of the data set is typically obvious, the specific fixed effects that affect the average responses for all subjects must be specified.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Some fixed effect coefficients are sufficient without corresponding random effects where as other fixed coefficients only represent an average where the individual units are random.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] These may be determined by incorporating random intercepts and slopes.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] In most situations, several related models are considered and the model that best represents a universal model is adopted.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] A key component of the mixed model is the incorporation of random effects with the fixed effect.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Fixed effects are often fitted to represent the underlying model.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] In Linear mixed models, the true regression of the population is linear, β.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] The fixed data is fitted at the highest level.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Random effects introduce statistical variability at different levels of the data hierarchy.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] These account for the unmeasured sources of variance that affect certain groups in the data.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] For example, the differences between student 1 and student 2 in the same class, or the differences between class 1 and class 2 in the same school.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Ronald Fisher introduced random effects models to study the correlations of trait values between relatives.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] In the 1950s, Charles Roy Henderson provided best linear unbiased estimates of fixed effects and best linear unbiased predictions of random effects.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Subsequently, mixed modeling has become a major area of statistical research, including work on computation of maximum likelihood estimates, non-linear mixed effects models, missing data in mixed effects models, and Bayesian estimation of mixed effects models.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Mixed models are applied in many disciplines where multiple correlated measurements are made on each unit of interest.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] They are prominently used in research involving human and animal subjects in fields ranging from genetics to marketing, and have also been used in baseball and industrial statistics.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] The mixed linear model association has improved the prevention of false positive associations.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Populations are deeply interconnected and the relatedness structure of population dynamics is extremely difficult to model without the use of mixed models.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Linear mixed models may not, however, be the only solution.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] LMM's have a constant-residual variance assumption that is sometimes violated when accounting for deeply associated continuous and binary traits.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] The inferred value of u for a category is then a category-specific intercept.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] If Z has additional columns, where the non-zero values are instead the value of an independent variable for an observation, then the corresponding inferred value of u is a category-specific slope for that independent variable.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] The prior distribution for the category intercepts and slopes is described by the covariance matrix G.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] where for example X′ is the matrix transpose of X and *R*−1 is the matrix inverse of R.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] The solutions to the MME, $\textstyle {\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}$ and $\textstyle {\hat {\boldsymbol {u}}}$ are best linear unbiased estimates and predictors for ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ and ${\boldsymbol {u}}$ , respectively.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] This is a consequence of the Gauss–Markov theorem when the conditional variance of the outcome is not scalable to the identity matrix.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] When the conditional variance is known, then the inverse variance weighted least squares estimate is best linear unbiased estimates.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] However, the conditional variance is rarely, if ever, known.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] So it is desirable to jointly estimate the variance and weighted parameter estimates when solving MMEs.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] One choice that analysts face with mixed models is which random effects (i.e., grouping variables, random intercepts, and random slopes) to include.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] One prominent recommendation in the context of confirmatory hypothesis testing is to adopt a "maximal" random effects structure, including all possible random effects justified by the experimental design, as a means to control Type I error rates.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] One method used to fit such mixed models is that of the expectation–maximization algorithm (EM) where the variance components are treated as unobserved nuisance parameters in the joint likelihood.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Currently, this is the method implemented in statistical software such as Python (statsmodels package) and as initial step only in R's nlme package lme().
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] The solution to the mixed model equations is a maximum likelihood estimate when the distribution of the errors is normal.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] Notably, while the canonical form proposed by Henderson is useful for theory, many popular software packages use a different formulation for numerical computation in order to take advantage of sparse matrix methods (e.g. lme4 and MixedModels.jl).
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] In the context of Bayesian methods, the brms package provides a user-friendly interface for fitting mixed models in R using Stan, allowing for the incorporation of prior distributions and the estimation of posterior distributions.
[src:mixed-effects-models/mixed-model] In python, Bambi provides a similarly streamlined approach for fitting mixed effects models using PyMC.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] In econometrics, a **random effects model**, also called a **variance components model**, is a statistical model where the model effects are random variables.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] It is a kind of hierarchical linear model, which assumes that the data being analysed are drawn from a hierarchy of different populations whose differences relate to that hierarchy.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] A random effects model is a special case of a mixed model.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] Contrast this to the biostatistics definitions, as biostatisticians use "fixed" and "random" effects to respectively refer to the population-average and subject-specific effects (and where the latter are generally assumed to be unknown, latent variables).
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] Random effect models assist in controlling for unobserved heterogeneity when the heterogeneity is constant over time and not correlated with independent variables.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] Two common assumptions can be made about the individual specific effect: the random effects assumption and the fixed effects assumption.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] The random effects assumption is that the individual unobserved heterogeneity is uncorrelated with the independent variables.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] The fixed effect assumption is that the individual specific effect can be correlated with the independent variables.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] If the random effects assumption holds, the random effects estimator is more efficient than the fixed effects model.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] Suppose m large elementary schools are chosen randomly from among thousands in a large country.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] Suppose also that n pupils of the same age are chosen randomly at each selected school.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] Their scores on a standard aptitude test are ascertained.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] Let $Y_{ij}$ be the score of the j -th pupil at the i -th school.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] where $\mu$ is the average test score for the entire population.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] In this model $U_{i}$ is the school-specific **random effect**: it measures the difference between the average score at school i and the average score in the entire country.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] The term $W_{ij}$ is the individual-specific random effect, i.e., it's the deviation of the j -th pupil's score from the average for the i -th school.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] The model can be augmented by including additional explanatory variables, which would capture differences in scores among different groups.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] where $\mathrm {Sex} _{ij}$ is a binary dummy variable and $\mathrm {ParentsEduc} _{ij}$ records, say, the average education level of a child's parents.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] This is a mixed model, not a purely random effects model, as it introduces fixed-effects terms for Sex and Parents' Education.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] The variance of $Y_{ij}$ is the sum of the variances $\tau ^{2}$ and $\sigma ^{2}$ of $U_{i}$ and $W_{ij}$ respectively.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] be the average, not of all scores at the i -th school, but of those at the i -th school that are included in the random sample.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] be respectively the sum of squares due to differences *within* groups and the sum of squares due to difference *between* groups.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] These "expected mean squares" can be used as the basis for estimation of the "variance components" $\sigma ^{2}$ and *$\tau ^{2}$*.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] The $\sigma ^{2}$ parameter is also called the intraclass correlation coefficient.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] For random effects models the marginal likelihoods are important.
[src:mixed-effects-models/random-effect] Random effects models used in practice include the Bühlmann model of insurance contracts and the Fay-Herriot model used for small area estimation.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] A popular repeated-measures design is the crossover study.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] A crossover study is a longitudinal study in which subjects receive a sequence of different treatments (or exposures).
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] While crossover studies can be observational studies, many important crossover studies are controlled experiments.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Crossover designs are common for experiments in many scientific disciplines, for example psychology, education, pharmaceutical science, and health care, especially medicine.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Randomized, controlled, crossover experiments are especially important in health care.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] In a randomized clinical trial, the subjects are randomly assigned treatments.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] When such a trial is a repeated measures design, the subjects are randomly assigned to a sequence of treatments.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] A crossover clinical trial is a repeated-measures design in which each patient is randomly assigned to a sequence of treatments, including at least two treatments (of which one may be a standard treatment or a placebo): Thus each patient crosses over from one treatment to another.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Nearly all crossover designs have "balance", which means that all subjects should receive the same number of treatments and that all subjects participate for the same number of periods.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] In most crossover trials, each subject receives all treatments.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] However, many repeated-measures designs are not crossovers: the longitudinal study of the sequential effects of repeated *treatments* need not use any "crossover", for example (Vonesh & Chinchilli; Jones & Kenward).
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Order effects may occur when a participant in an experiment is able to perform a task and then perform it again.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Examples of order effects include performance improvement or decline in performance, which may be due to learning effects, boredom or fatigue.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] The impact of order effects may be smaller in long-term longitudinal studies or by counterbalancing using a crossover design.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] In this technique, two groups each perform the same tasks or experience the same conditions, but in reverse order.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] With two tasks or conditions, four groups are formed.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Counterbalancing attempts to take account of two important sources of systematic variation in this type of design: practice and boredom effects.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Both might otherwise lead to different performance of participants due to familiarity with or tiredness to the treatments.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] It may not be possible for each participant to be in all conditions of the experiment (i.e. time constraints, location of experiment, etc.).
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Severely diseased subjects tend to drop out of longitudinal studies, potentially biasing the results.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] In these cases mixed effects models would be preferable as they can deal with missing values.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Mean regression may affect conditions with significant repetitions.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Maturation may affect studies that extend over time.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Events outside the experiment may change the response between repetitions.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Repeated measures analysis of variance (rANOVA) is a commonly used statistical approach to repeated measure designs.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] With such designs, the repeated-measure factor (the qualitative independent variable) is the within-subjects factor, while the dependent quantitative variable on which each participant is measured is the dependent variable.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] One of the greatest advantages to rANOVA, as is the case with repeated measures designs in general, is the ability to partition out variability due to individual differences.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] In a repeated measures design it is possible to partition subject variability from the treatment and error terms.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] In such a case, variability can be broken down into between-treatments variability (or within-subjects effects, excluding individual differences) and within-treatments variability.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] In reference to the general structure of the F-statistic, it is clear that by partitioning out the between-subjects variability, the F-value will increase because the sum of squares error term will be smaller resulting in a smaller MSError.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] It is noteworthy that partitioning variability reduces degrees of freedom from the F-test, therefore the between-subjects variability must be significant enough to offset the loss in degrees of freedom.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] If between-subjects variability is small this process may actually reduce the F-value.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] As with all statistical analyses, specific assumptions should be met to justify the use of this test.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] Violations can moderately to severely affect results and often lead to an inflation of type 1 error.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] With the rANOVA, standard univariate and multivariate assumptions apply.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] The rANOVA also requires that certain multivariate assumptions be met, because a multivariate test is conducted on difference scores.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] As with other analysis of variance tests, the rANOVA makes use of an F statistic to determine significance.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] One of the most commonly reported effect size statistics for rANOVA is partial eta-squared (ηp2).
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] It is also common to use the multivariate η2 when the assumption of sphericity has been violated, and the multivariate test statistic is reported.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] A third effect size statistic that is reported is the generalized η2, which is comparable to ηp2 in a one-way repeated measures ANOVA.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] It has been shown to be a better estimate of effect size with other within-subjects tests.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] rANOVA is not always the best statistical analysis for repeated measure designs.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] The rANOVA is vulnerable to effects from missing values, imputation, unequivalent time points between subjects and violations of sphericity.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] These issues can result in sampling bias and inflated rates of Type I error.
[src:mixed-effects-models/repeated-measures-design] In such cases it may be better to consider use of a linear mixed model.
[src:mixed-effects-models/restricted-maximum-likelihood] In the case of variance component estimation, the original data set is replaced by a set of contrasts calculated from the data, and the likelihood function is calculated from the probability distribution of these contrasts, according to the model for the complete data set.
[src:mixed-effects-models/restricted-maximum-likelihood] In particular, REML is used as a method for fitting linear mixed models.
[src:mixed-effects-models/restricted-maximum-likelihood] In contrast to the earlier maximum likelihood estimation, REML can produce unbiased estimates of variance and covariance parameters.
[src:mixed-effects-models/restricted-maximum-likelihood] The idea underlying REML estimation was put forward by M.
[src:mixed-effects-models/restricted-maximum-likelihood] The first description of the approach applied to estimating components of variance in unbalanced data was by Desmond Patterson and Robin Thompson of the University of Edinburgh in 1971, although they did not use the term REML.
[src:mixed-effects-models/restricted-maximum-likelihood] A review of the early literature was given by Harville.
